  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="NA12-kiḷavi">itu tōḻi yuṭaṉpōk kañcuvittatu.</p>
        <p xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante induces fear of elopement.</p>
      </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="NA12">
<l>            viḷampaḻaṅ kamaḻuṅ kamañcūṟ kuḻicip</l>
<l>            pācan tiṉṟa tēykāṉ matta</l>
<l>            neyteri yiyakkam veḷiṉmutaṉ muḻaṅkum</l>
<l>            vaikupular viṭiyaṉ meykarantu taṉkā</l>
<l>            lariyamai cilampu kaḻīip paṉmāṇ </l>
<l>            varipuṉai pantoṭu vaiiya celvō</l>
<l>            ḷivaikāṇ ṭōṟu nōvar mātō</l>
<l>            vaḷiyarō vaḷiyareṉ ṉāyat tōreṉa</l>
<l>            nummoṭu varavutā ṉayaravun</l>
<l>            taṉvarait taṉṟiyuṅ kaluḻntaṉa kaṇṇē.</l>

        </lg>
        <lg xml:lang="en">
        <l rend="indent">When the churning stick's base thunders,<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">yakkam veḷil mutal muḻaṅkum</term>: or it "thunders melodiously".</note> in motion to clear the butter,</l>
        <l rend="indent">in the milk-mixture(?), [its] foot(?)<note place="foot">Strangely enough <term xml:lang="ta">kāl</term> seems here to refer to the head of the churning stick, for that is the portion on which the rope is fastened, while the actual foot should be submerged in the liquid.</note> diminished, eaten away by the cord,</l>
        <l rend="indent2">in the pot filled to the brim<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kaman cūl</term>: literally "the fully pregnant pot".</note>, smelling of wood-apple,</l>
        <l>in the oncoming dawn that remains she would go,</l>
        <l rend="indent2">[her] body disguised, the anklets removed from her feet,</l>
        <l rend="indent3">so that the [tinkling] pieces [inside] be still,</l>
        <l rend="indent3">put away<note place="foot">Here we have the alternative of reading <term xml:lang="ta">vaiiya</term> (on which depend the two absolutives <term xml:lang="ta">karantu</term> and <term xml:lang="ta">kaḻīi</term>) either as a perfective peyareccam or as an infinitive. Above the preference has been given to the peyareccam, taking the <term xml:lang="ta">celvōḷ</term> as a finite verb referring to HER going away with HIM. The traditional understanding reads an infinitive, which makes a kind of auxiliary of <term xml:lang="ta">cel</term>: "she would go to put away...". This reading is supported by the variant <term xml:lang="ta">vaippiya</term>, an unequivocal infinitive.</note> with the ball tied many times with [cloth-]stripes</l>
        <l>– [when thinking]: “whenever they see these they will certainly<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">mātō</term> seems to be a certain expectation connected with hypothetical/future acts (cf. KT 144.5, 253.4).</note> ache.</l>
        <l rend="indent4">Ah, pitiable, pitiable they, my companions”,</l>
        <l rend="indent3">even when she engaged herself in coming with you,</l>
        <l>and in spite of controlling herself(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">varaittu</term>: apart from a few occurrences in the Kalit., this is the only passage where we find this form. It probably has to be analysed as appellative noun of <term xml:lang="ta">varai</term> "limit", but how to account for syntax here? If it were the eyes she is controlling we would actually expect <term xml:lang="ta">varaiya</term>, n.pl.</note> [her] eyes dimmed.</l>
        
    </lg>
